      "text": "post commenting\nshowing to users. ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "center",
      "verticalAlign": "middle",
      "containerId": "u6GdxDmulDSscuookpE0a",
      "originalText": "post commenting showing to users. ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "L_qBhMcDvlZUNytpbosNk",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -2721.5795598451973,
      "y": -11638.467408654342,
      "width": 1643.3990478515625,
      "height": 625,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 90,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "ai",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1654476812,
      "version": 1997,
      "versionNonce": 1746256683,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1773030536497,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Deep dive:\n1. scalability: aim for msg size< 1MB . One broker can handle upto 1TB of data, 1M msgs/second.\n Choose a good partition key which divides the data into right patititons.\n\n2. In case of hot key, all the events might go to one partition. \nThe solution can be:\n   1. remove the key. \n   2. make it compound key: add some random number like 100+random(10) if 100 was hot key then load will be divided in 10 servers. Or \n      any other id can be added 100(partitiion key)+ Userid.\n   3. backpressure: ask the producer to slow down. It is done via checking the offset, if the offset is more than the producer slows down.\n\n3. fault tolerance and durability: \n    1. keep acks in the code: number of acks to show that message has been recieved. Higher more durable but higher latency. Here acks means the number of replica \npartitions should ack when a message is sent to kafka. \n    2. replication factor\n\n4. what happens when consumer goes down? \n   1. It will read from offset. It might happen post processing the event, the consumer went down. In case atleast one delivery semantics come into picture.\n   2. error and retries: in case of failure the event can be pushed to Retry topic. After multiple failures again can be pushed to dead letter queue which will be seen by \n       developer to check what events got failed. \n\n5. perf optmzn: \n    1. retention policy: how may days the events will stay in kafka\n    2. retention by bytes: default 1GB limit then it goes for deleting\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Deep dive:\n1. scalability: aim for msg size< 1MB . One broker can handle upto 1TB of data, 1M msgs/second.\n Choose a good partition key which divides the data into right patititons.\n\n2. In case of hot key, all the events might go to one partition. \nThe solution can be:\n   1. remove the key. \n   2. make it compound key: add some random number like 100+random(10) if 100 was hot key then load will be divided in 10 servers. Or \n      any other id can be added 100(partitiion key)+ Userid.\n   3. backpressure: ask the producer to slow down. It is done via checking the offset, if the offset is more than the producer slows down.\n\n3. fault tolerance and durability: \n    1. keep acks in the code: number of acks to show that message has been recieved. Higher more durable but higher latency. Here acks means the number of replica \npartitions should ack when a message is sent to kafka. \n    2. replication factor\n\n4. what happens when consumer goes down? \n   1. It will read from offset. It might happen post processing the event, the consumer went down. In case atleast one delivery semantics come into picture.\n   2. error and retries: in case of failure the event can be pushed to Retry topic. After multiple failures again can be pushed to dead letter queue which will be seen by \n       developer to check what events got failed. \n\n5. perf optmzn: \n    1. retention policy: how may days the events will stay in kafka\n    2. retention by bytes: default 1GB limit then it goes for deleting\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "5_3FMvH-H7J-oJcHqgmxm",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -3086.719476119132,
      "y": -11014.641027647283,
      "width": 577.77978515625,
      "height": 70,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 90,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "aj",
